	<div class="w3-display-container mySlides2 fade">
	<div class="numbertext2">1 / 3</div>
	 <p id="caption_title_standard_of_care">STANDARD OF CARE</p>
	  <%=image_tag "3.1.jpg", id: "default" %>
	   <p id="caption_definition">Your conduct will always be compared to that of a reasonable defendant under similar circumstances.<br> There are various “degrees” to standard of care, depending on the given situation.<br>Examples include “slight” and “great.”</p>
	   <p id="caption_story">“Andy, looking down, texting while crossing the street, and not looking where he’s going, can be viewed as breaching a “slight” standard of care.<br>Andy driving a bus full of children blindfolded would be viewed as breaching a “great” standard of care.</p>
	  </div>
	</div>

	<div class="w3-display-container mySlides2 fade">
	<div class="numbertext2">2 / 3</div>
	<p id="caption_title_if_a_child_is_negligent">IF A CHILD IS NEGLIGENT</p>
	 <%=image_tag "3.2.jpg", id: "default" %>
	    <p id="caption_definition">...he or she will be judged accordingly to a specific age group, experience level, or education relative to other children unless the child engages in inherently dangerous activity, in which this case the child will be held to an adult standard of care or the parent/guardian will be liable.</p>
	   <p id="caption_story">“Abigail breaks a vase in an antique shop. She will be judged accordingly to someone of her age.<br>Abigail, driving a tractor, runs over the Stephensons’ flowers. Because that activity is inherently dangerous, and because Andy let her mow the lawn so he could watch the big game, he will be held liable for Abigail’s actions."</p>
		</div>
	</div>

	<div class="w3-display-container mySlides2 fade">
	<div class="numbertext2">3 / 3</div>
	    <p id="caption_title_gross_negligence">GROSS NEGLIGENCE</p>
	      <%=image_tag "3.3.jpg", id: "default" %>
	    <p id="caption_definition">Being reckless with disregard for other peoples’ safety. An act in which you will be liable.</p>
	   <p id="caption_story">“Andy playing paintball in the park where a child is put in danger (for being too close to the activity) can be considered a shameful act of “gross negligence."</p>
	  </div>
